ompson seeks to explain not only how interactions differ in the selection pressures they exert on species, but also when interactions are most likely to lead to coevolution. In this era of climate change and swiftly transforming environments, the ideas Thompson puts forward in Interaction and Coevolution are more relevant than ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCoevolution. 0aEvolution (Biology). 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aevolution, species, interaction, coevolution, adaptation, natural selection, genetics, science, biology, nonfiction, mutualism, antagonism, speciation, population, community structure, climate change, global warming, nature, environment, environmentalism, conservation, preservation, ecology, parasitism, grazing, predation, competition, habitat, mutual dependence, ecosystem.1 aThompson, John N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226127323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226127323/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles